node.title: Cyclic dependency detected in object ordering
node.bodyText:
Hello,
In recent days, I updated the MOOSE version on my computer. However, when i run my previous working case, it fails now and shows "Cyclic dependency detected in object ordering " :

i noted that it is a new function added in MOOSE  (moose/framework/src/loops/ComputeInitialConditionThread.C) . Does anyone knows why my case fails now?
Besides, the error information reported many materials which are not dependency acturally. For example,  it shows "fuel_eigen_strain -> SiC_hc" ,but there is no calling relationship between them.

If a material object A requests a material property declared in another material object B, then A depends on B. There are other ways of introducing dependency, but this is most likely your case.
This error signals poorly designed code. You have three options:

Reorganize/redesign the material objects
Suppress the error, either by turning off the dependency check (I'm not sure if that's possible), or by reverting back to an earlier version of moose.
In some cases, cyclic dependency can be fixed by making some materials discrete.

@hugary1995 Thanks for your reply. I‘m now simulating the themo-mechanical behaviors of an object which has multilayer structures.

Each structure is a separate block (block 1 to 5).  In each separate block, i defined its material objects of HeatConduction and TensorMechanics. However,  the error information shows when calculating the strain of block 1 (fuel), it calls the material property in block 3 (SiC). The error in calculating stress is similar.
I noted in my source code when calculating the strain of block 1 (fuel_eigen_strain), it shouled get the material property "density" from its HeatConductionMaterial (kernel_hc).  Acturally the material property "density" is also declared in other blocks.
I wonder if Moose's new function (moose/framework/src/loops/ComputeInitialConditionThread.C)  considers these "density" to be the same, even although the block is specified in the input file.

You can debug it by adding the following snippet to your input file:
[Debug]
  show_material_props = true
[]

node.title: Diffusion Controlled Evaporation with Displacement / Node Deactivation Approach
node.bodyText:
I am looking to model a diffusion controlled evaporation process with mass loss resulting in uniform material recession at the surface; however, I am struggling to come up with a good approach for modeling the recession and shifting of the boundary position with material loss? A coupled displacement condition seems overly complicated and might create errors arising from the displaced mesh. Alternatively, I was considering node deactivation, but I am not sure how to then shift the applied boundary condition.
If I could get some advice on an approach to this, that would be great!
@cticenhour @aeslaughter  I think would have had a similar challenge with additive manufacturing (boundary advancing instead of receding)
I've not done any manufacturing modeling where I've manipulated the mesh, but @SudiptaBiswas and @dewenyushu has done work in additive manufacturing modeling specifically.

This looks like something that can be done with the element subdomain modifier, e.g., CoupledVarThresholdElementSubdomainModifier
To use it, you will need to define two subdomains in your input. One is the 'active' subdomain containing the elements that belongs to the fluid ('active') material. The other one is the 'dummy' subdomain which contains the elements that belongs to the gas ('loss') material.
Meanwhile, if you do not solve anything for the evaporated phase, the kernels and materials blocks need to be block-restricted, i.e., defined only in the 'active' subdomain.
The evaporation of material can be modeled by moving the elements from the 'active' subdomain to the 'dummy' subdomain. This can be taken care of by the CoupledVarThresholdElementSubdomainModifier. You will need to couple it with the variable that represents the material loss (e.g., density) and specify a threshold value, below which the element is treated as belonging to the loss material thus can be moved to a 'dummy' subdomain. If you specify the moving_boundary_name, in the CoupledVarThresholdElementSubdomainModifier, the boundary between the fluid and gas phases should be updated correspondingly.
Thank you, this was very helpful! If I am not interested in solving for the gas phase, what would be the best approach for nullifying the influence of variables now in the dummy blocks?

You should be able to use the NullKernel for the dummy blocks for this purpose. Make sure that you have all your kernels properly defined in corresponding subdomains by including the block = '<block_ids>' in every kernel.
Either that or you block-restrict the variables out of the dummy blocks.
this later approach will be cheaper because the matrix will be smaller.
Yeah, I agree with @GiudGiud  - just to add that you may need to turn off kernel_coverage_check and/or material_coverage_check if you go with the later.

Block restriction seems like the right move.
I have also noticed that the defined boundary seems to persist at the original location even when the moving_boundary_name option is supplied. The result, when opened in paraview, shows two boundaries of the same name, one at the original location and the other at the dummy domain interface. Furthermore, it appears that boundary condition property at the dummy domain interface inherits from the persistent one - i.e. the flux at the interface falls to zero. I couldn't find an example in the MOOSE test files that moves a pre-existing boundary (only one that creates a new one), so I am unsure if this is a bug or an issue with my implementation.

Glad that it works to some degree.
Would you mind sharing some screen shots to illustrate the issue?

Yes, after poking around more it seems the issue is the the boundary condition no longer applies to the new boundary defined by the user object. Here I am tracking the boundary condition value over time and note that the flux (defined by simple Neumann condition) falls to zero once the boundary is moved - creating a natural (zero flux) boundary condition at the new, moved, boundary. I suspect that the original boundary condition is set to a quadrature point and needs to be updated with the moving boundary.

    dim = 2
    nx = 100

    xmin = 0
    xmax = 1

git submodule foreach --recursive git clean -xfd

Then load the calculation and do a single time step and set the nl_abs_tol and nl_rel_tol loose enough to always accept the result
then look at the output

The convergence issue here is caused by an inappropriate choice of the path following algorithm.
The load displacement curve of a plastic material typically looks like this

In your input file you are using a Neumann BC to "follow" this curve, which is equivalent to prescribing the y component of this curve. It is apparent that no solution exist pass the ultimate strength. Numerically, this relates to non-convergence with many inverted elements. You are essentially asking the model to perform an impossible task.
In this case, you'll have to change the path following algorithm to a displacement-controlled one. That is changing the Neumann BC to a Dirichlet BC. You can add a postprocessor to output the force:

  [fy]
  []
  [fz]
  []
[]

    save_in = 'fx fy fz'
  []
[]

[Postprocessors]
  [force]
    type = NodalSum
    variable = fz
    boundary = front
  []
[]
You'll see that the force starts decreasing after certain point, and that corresponds to the point at which Neumann BC fails.

My plasticity curves/hardening functions don't look like that though. I'm effectively using an elastic bilinear plasticity, which looks like this:

The hardening functions are linear and extrapolated so increasing strain will always require increasing stress. This was a simplification I made to attempt to get the plasticity to converge without any success.
EDIT: To be clear this isn't a plot of my exact functions, just an image off google. I have a youngs modulus of 95000, tangent modulus of 1200 at 0 degrees, 1000 at 100 degrees and 800 at 200 degrees, with yield stresses of 1000, 800 and 600 respectively.

You are mixing the concept of material point constitutive model and macroscopic load displacement curve. Linear hardening still gives rise to necking. Please try my suggestion above.
